content: Not many here, but the best ones always come! :)
Let us have the check now.
shuwang, Xespok, Red_Zombie, yyfcsd, mayhem, fallnavy, scm2000, luwenzhe, yun_shou, coco_yuang, weigui, slamduk, Guest338, virag, HEX77, shaoping.
Today, I wish to bring us back in time a bit, and look into the games played over 20 years ago.
Namely, we will look at the USSR mail tournament in 1883.
in 1983 there were not many renju players in Russia,
only a few of them were good players.
The famous players of that time were for example Biryukov and Maslyayev.
Biryukov was maybe the best USSR player in around 1988.
In fact, he had the right to participate in the first World Championship in Japan 1989.
but he was not among the 3 players that represented USSR in Japan WC.
The reason was related to his work, as I know.
It was not easy for some people to get the permit to travel abroad in USSR times.
I have met and played with Biryukov only once,
it was the B tournament of WC in 1991,
I played with him in the last round.
As you can imagine, 6 dan was very high and respected rank at that time.
Today we will see the game of 1983, between Biryukov and Maslyayev.
These first moves are all familiar to you.
In fact, all the 13 moves are very clear.
The theory has not changed past 21 years.
What is your opinion, students, is this variant black or white advantage?
I want to hear everyone, so we will know where we stand today
this is a very interesting question.
the opinions tend to change here very often.
Actually, even 21 years later, people still argue about it.
mostly the argument is about the principles of evaluation.
so some people say it is black advantage.
but some others say, it does not matter if black is strong. as long as white is sure to defend, then in the end white will be better - so as a conclusion it is white advantage
it will finally come down to the simple facts - who is a better player, who makes less mistakes,
and who knows more theory here.
Back then, the theory was very "obvious".
it was balanced if one side does not have clear advantage
Both black and white players played with simple style - take basic attack and defense points.
hehe,i keep my thinking,black will good.
of course, you need to think this way, shaoping, if you are black.
You must think "positive" about your chances.
Just like when I played with Chingin in last WC, I was black,
and I kept telling myself black is sooooo good
As you can see, it is all very straight.
therefore, their games were somewhat predictable
what do you think about defense?
what is a predictable defense move here?
whenever possible, they made the most logical defense -
blocking most spaceous direction, from the outside.
sometimes most logical defense not good
at that time, the tactics was not good.
people did not think of building the connections,
or cutting them, as in defense.
in this case, the line 7_17 is a serious connection line
if 20 years ago the players would be asked, what is the most dangerous black line,
the reason of their thinking is,
they just look at the "local impact" of the black pair
seems black win in lower side
and the connections had low value
Today, in modern renju, the skill of tactics is high
today's masters would immediately say that the line 7_17 is the most dangerous.
and the other two lines, although locally active, are not eventually dangerous at all.
at that they played gomoku, in gomoku not so interesting connections and no many long games
Let us first look the game to the end,
and then we will critically look over the move 18
and find best solution for white.
where should this black three be stopped from?
yyfcsd, slamduk, Red_Zombie, Xespok, luwenzhe, mayhem, scm2000, fallnavy, shuwang, whte, Guest338, virag, shaoping, coco_yuang, yun_shou.
some fatal error must have occured
it is a nice break time
In the game, Maslyayev played 20 to the left, as one should.
And move 21 was played to k6.
Please note, it was the mail tournament.
Do you know how mail tournaments were played 20 years ago?
they used the post cards and letters of snail mail.
we sent one postcard from SU to Hungary
Does anyone of you have such experience?
may be postal dove (pigeons) better solution :)))
the thinking time was maybe around 40 days
Usually, the speed of delivery was like 10 days
people used the stamp record on the postcard, to check time log
but games did not last too long,
inner side USSR it was ok, but outside not
usually, to speed up the games,
like, if you play 12-g6 then I put 13-g7
so, sometimes, i sent the if-branches up to 7 moves deep
in the endgame and in the opening it is good
so if he accepted one branch, we had 7 moves done at once
this should be done also on RC tournaments
it was good in theory variants, such as this one.
It might be that one player made suggestion up to 13th move
in the middle game , it is not good beacuse opponent can find mistake in branch :)
and upon accepting, the game jumped to move 13
any possibility of if you play 12-h6, then I resign?:)
so when people sent me the branches
I always digged into them, to find weaknesses
and sometimes it saved me from loss
I remember, I used branches in sure win situations
actually, we can call it a grandfather of todays homeworks
from the moment I had vct win,
i made the tree of all moves and branches
but back then, really lots of handwork
in fact, the earliest students of renjuclass still might remember our first hws
they were also hand made trees
yes, can be found in early lesson materials
now it feels like Stone Age
sent by email, but branches are manually composed
like, some people made with notation
some people sent image files, one by one
or as the Word document files
one thing about mail tournaments was -
it often took over 1-2 months to resume game
we had tons of free time
Let us look at the game here,
it was a mail tournament, and commonly, players seeing the sure win, sent their opponents the branches, proving the win on any block.
and then if opponent did not see any bugs there, he just resigned without making any move.
Maslyayev did not resign at move 22
which means, Biryukov did not send out the branches
maybe because of no win, or he was too lazy?
so, the more branches, the less money
Now, lets see, why Maslyayev resigned.
may be he want avoid 22 i6
maybe he sent, and white found bugs?
Who can show win, say ME
yy, if he sent branch, then white can accept and submit the whole branch into game
but as you saw, just 1 black move and then white gave up
sometimes, when people sent me a buggy branch,
he did not find win in time
I accepted it happily and submitted it,
and also wrote "you could have won with..."
How about here? Is it win too? who can show?
Ok, since move 22 was made, we know that no branches were sent.
So maybe when making move 21, Biryukov was not sure of his win yet.
I wonder where the problem was.
thats why his eyes are bigger
maybe that's why 19 is needed. If black can win in the lower side, then 19 not needed
lets now quickly look at the situation here
What should white improve on move 18?
L11 maybe not good because it does not really breat the inside connectiom
Lets look the mostly suggested h7 move.
on email game i hate 40 moves long VCF :)
seems j7 stone help black much
we spoke about that 7-17 line most important defend
the stone 16 is not helping in defense at all
it is put into the outer space
actually, 9-15 line help black attack too
actually, we will not know the clear conclusion today.
people did not conclude in 21 years,
and its hard to do it now with 90 mins
but you all got plenty of ideas to think about
at least we learned that black is stronger than many people thought
and white needs a very careful defense
This lesson was a nice travel to the history of renju.
and we found that the theory and problems back then are still important today.
Maybe you can do more research about it,
They are valuable for our dan title system.
and see you all next Tuesday
